{
  "_comment": "Indian brand name -> the molecule(s) it actually contains. Display is 'generic (BRAND)', so the brand is never lost -- it is what appears on the strip in the cupboard and what the doctor wrote.",
  "_why": "Without this you cannot answer 'is this patient on metformin?' -- they may be, but the summary says TENEPRIDE M and GALVUS MET and GLUCONORM G2, which are three different brands of it. Nor can you catch a duplicate: GLUCONORM G2 and GEMER are both glimepiride+metformin. A brand list is a list of packages, not of drugs.",
  "_confirmed": "confirmed=false means I am NOT sure of the molecule and it must not be trusted. Guessing a drug is the most dangerous thing this system could do. Those rows stay in review until a human checks the strip or the prescription.",
  "_device": "device=true means it is not a drug at all -- it came out of a discharge medication list but is equipment.",
